JOHANNESBURG – A wildlife park in eastern Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), which is home to critically endangered mountain gorillas, will remain closed to tourism following an attack in which two British tourists were abducted and later released, AP reported. READ: Ranger killed, British tourists kidnapped in DRC national park Virunga National Park, which halted tourism after the May 11 incident in which a ranger was killed, said on Monday the restriction will continue until “further notice". Eastern Congo has been the scene of successive waves of violence in recent decades. Rebel groups and militias still control large swathes of the territory. Nearly 200 rangers have died protecting the park in recent years. - Additional reporting by eNCA African News Agency